":"Photograph: Internet","mediaId":"259fcff787eee0866064482fd545e94e9958e415","picdarUrn":"GD*51046865","width":"380"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/13/1426267792225/866ff5d1-af2b-4fbe-8f91-2f59e4f9f56f-620x372.jpeg","typeData":{"copyright":"Publicity image","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/13/1426267792225/866ff5d1-af2b-4fbe-8f91-2f59e4f9f56f-620x372.jpeg","source":"Internet","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"New mission? Denis Lawson as Wedge Antilles, the X-Wing fighter pilot in Star Wars.","height":"372","credit":"Photograph: Internet","mediaId":"259fcff787eee0866064482fd545e94e9958e415","picdarUrn":"GD*51046865","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Who I gotta call to stop the Ghostbusters universe expanding?","webPublicationDate":"2015-03-13T16:45:59Z","sectionId":"film","id":"film/2015/mar/13/ghostbusters-universe-star-wars","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/46hp7","standfirst":"<p>The Star Wars and Marvel cinematic universes work by riffing on favourite characters. Ghostbusters just doesn’t fit the mould<br></p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>The term “cinematic universe” didn’t exist prior to 2008, when Marvel debuted its first in-house superhero epic, Iron Man. But ever since the Disney-owned studio proved with the $1.5bn (£1bn) The Avengers that it’s possible to build a series of related properties that unite to form an even more enormous box office megalith, Hollywood has been all over it.</p> <p>First came the predictable news that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jun/13/warner-bros-announce-dc-comics-superhero-films\">rival Warner Bros was planning its own series of linked superhero movies</a> based on its rights to the DC Comics back catalogue (famous for Batman, Superman, the Justice League and so on). Then Sony announced doomed proposals to exploit its limited rights to Spider-Man by pushing for <a href=\"http://screenrant.com/venom-movie-amazing-spider-man-sinister-six-sony/2/\">films based on related characters such as Venom and the Sinister Six team of supervillains</a>. Twentieth Century Fox was at one point expected to follow suit with a run of movies based on individual X-Men characters, but at the moment seems happy putting out the odd Wolverine episode in among its series of films about the ongoing mutant battle between Professor X and Magneto.</p> <p>Then two years ago it emerged that Marvel owner Disney planned to exploit its newly attained Star Wars rights by building a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/16/star-wars-films-origins-standalone\">second cinematic universe incorporating several standalone “origin tales”</a> (featuring iconic characters such as Han Solo, Boba Fett and Obi Wan Kenobi) on top of its previously announced trilogy of new movies. And so, the universe concept leapt the genetic gap from comic-book movies to space opera, and a thousand tunnel-visioned Hollywood executives began to wonder if the idea might work for their own properties.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e99a3a9917c9b270be220fcff3cc125a8fc97efe\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/12/1426183511846/e2c9e6a0-0611-49f7-89c0-4dc317bcfd17-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Slimer in Ghostbusters\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Hold tight for a Simer origins movie … Ghostbusters, 1984.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Allstar/Columbia</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The phenomenon appears to have reached its zenith this week following reports that Sony is planning a cinematic universe based on Ghostbusters. So we won’t just be getting the recently announced reboot starring Melissa McCarthy, Kristen Wiig, et al, but also <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/10/ghostbusters-cinematic-universe-channing-tatum-sony\">a “male” Ghostbusters movie featuring Channing Tatum</a>, as well as various nebulous future outings set in the same world. Hold tight for a Slimer origins movie, perhaps charting the chubby green spirit’s descent into incorporeal corpulence, or a big-screen prequel about the early years of Gozer and Zuul. I’d pay money to see a film about the continuing adventures in high-end accountancy of Louis Tully, but only because it’s been such a long time since we saw Rick Moranis in the multiplexes.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote\"> <blockquote> <p>Marvel was inspired by a desire to recreate the excitement of long-established comic books</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>The problem here is that Sony seems to have completely misunderstood how Marvel delivered its incredibly successful series of linked films and, more importantly, why the Disney-owned studio struck upon the concept in the first place. The original cinematic universe was not magicked out of thin air by a Doctor Strange-like movie bigwig to increase profits (though the studio undoubtedly saw the potential for exploiting its fabulous back catalogue of superheroes). It was inspired by a desire to recreate the excitement of long-established comic books, whereby different characters routinely cross-pollinate, on the big screen. The studio introduced the likes of Iron Man, Thor and Captain America in their own outings before uniting them in The Avengers – because that’s pretty much exactly what has been happening in print over the past 50 or 60 years.</p> <p>There’s a parallel with Star Wars, too. While the live-action film series itself has always remained a linear concoction, the expanded universe of novels and comics long ago proved that fans were interested in exploring a space opera beyond the stories of Luke and Anakin Skywalker. Characters such as Yoda and Solo have become so iconic over the past 35 years that few fans would begrudge Disney exploiting them for standalone origins movies, provided the quality levels were maintained and the Jedi master didn’t zip around the screen like a CGI frog in a blender, Attack of the Clones-style. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"8ee863a833fabae65750e6adba92c0c3715d8f7c\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/12/1426183814540/ba0c3de3-758c-48fa-b127-ebe9af6dca2f-460x195.jpeg\" alt=\"Hayden Christensen as Anakin Skywalker in Star Wars: Episode III – Revenge of the Sith. \" width=\"460\" height=\"195\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A wider space opera … Hayden Christensen as Anakin Skywalker in Star Wars: Episode III – Revenge of the Sith.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Lucasfilm/ILM</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ghostbusters, wonderful as the original 1984 comedy is, simply doesn’t fit the remit for expansion into a wider universe. The weak 1989 sequel did little to create a sense of a richer world of ghosts and spirits beyond Manhattan, and if Sony is planning to adapt episodes of either of the two animated TV series to carry the Ghostbusters name then it really is in trouble. The news that the rights-starved studio wants to go down the cinematic universe route is likely to be met with incredulity, just at a time when the film series’ revival had been creating such positive buzz.</p> <p>People like the idea of Feig’s female Ghostbusters, because it sounds like something a little different. But reaction to the Tatum-led “male” film has been <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/03/10/boy-led-ghostbusters-announced-because-girls-cant-even-have-one-series-for-themselves/\">mixed to say the least</a>, largely because it <a href=\"http://www.slashfilm.com/infographic-hollywoods-waning-creativity/\">sounds like nothing new at all</a>. So one can only imagine the response on Twitter when Sony, which is <a href=\"http://www.latino-review.com/news/exclusive-sonys-now-working-on-an-aunt-may-movie\">rumoured to have once considered proposals for an Aunt May movie</a> linked to its Spider-Man rights, reveals its far-out ideas for the next stage of the Ghostbusters universe. The studio will be called out, rightly, for clutching at spectral straws. </p>","headline":"Who I gotta call to stop the Ghostbusters universe expanding?","trailText":"The Star Wars and Marvel cinematic universes work by riffing on favourite characters. Ghostbusters just doesn’t fit the mould<br>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/12/1426183359127/f4c213d2-73dc-4e23-b457-89093c309708-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"861","commentable":"true","byline":"Ben Child","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-03-16T16:45:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/13/ghostbusters-universe-star-wars","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/mar/13/ghostbusters-universe-star-wars","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/series/week-in-geek","webTitle":"Week in geek","description":"Ben Child's guide to the world of comic book, superhero, sci fi and fantasy movies. <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/BenChildFilm\">Follow him on Twitter</a>","type":"series","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/week-in-geek","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/series/week-in-geek","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/ghostbusters","webTitle":"Ghostbusters","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/ghostbusters","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/ghostbusters","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/superhero-movies","webTitle":"Superhero movies","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/superhero-movies","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/superhero-movies","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"cultu