webTitle":"Kristin Scott Thomas: five best moments","webPublicationDate":"2015-03-13T14:29:28Z","sectionId":"culture","id":"culture/filmblog/2015/mar/13/kristin-scott-thomas-five-best-moments","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/46thv","standfirst":"<p>The greatest English and French performances from the star of Suite Française</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>While Kristin Scott Thomas <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jan/31/kristin-scott-thomas-interview\">may have threatened to quit working in movies on occasion</a>, a relatively steady stream of film roles suggests that retirement is still a long way off. This week sees her effortlessly stealing wartime romance Suite Française from star Michelle Williams as a tyrannical mother-in-law, and to celebrate, we’ve gone through her varied CV to recall her greatest hits.</p> <h2>Bitter Moon</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ2db-CD7xc\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/NZ2db-CD7xc?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>Before she bitchily lusted all over Hugh Grant in Four Weddings and a Funeral, Scott Thomas played his wife in Roman Polanski’s kinky psychodrama. While Grant’s sexual obsession dominated the proceedings, Scott Thomas sashayed her way into the spotlight in this memorably lurid scene where she enjoys a crowd-pleasing cruise ship dance with Emmanuelle Seigner. Bonus points for staying on her feet while on stormy seas.</p> <h2>The English Patient</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z40Tipkm4IA\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/z40Tipkm4IA?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B57bOy2Dzjg\">While Elaine Benes might have loathed it</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/ng-interactive/2015/feb/07/starry-starry-night-oscar-winners-on-hollywoods-biggest-prize?CMP=share_btn_tw\">Lauren Bacall resented it</a>, Anthony Minghella’s romantic melodrama was buried in praise on release, especially from the Academy, who gave Scott Thomas her first and only nomination to date. Her tragic arc as a woman left to die alone in the desert gave this scene, as she begged her lover to return, an unforgettably haunting edge.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/suite-franaise-michelle-williams-founders-in-saccharine-version-nemirovsky-bestseller\">Suite Française review – Michelle Williams sleepwalks through wartime</a> </p> </aside>  <h2>I’ve Loved You So Long</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BX7PckDUMA4\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/BX7PckDUMA4?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>While the 90s might have seen her corner the respectable, if easily corrupted, English wife market, the late noughties transported Scott Thomas to France where she provided some of her greatest work. The best of which was her challenging role as a woman released from prison after 15 years. A muted performance finally gives way to a devastating breakdown in this flawlessly executed final scene.</p> <h2>Leaving</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JdB4YXN_-DE\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/JdB4YXN_-DE?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>Another one of her finest French performances allowed her the chance to take what could have been a soapy melodrama (woman cheats on husband with younger man) and enrich it with depth and pathos. In this moment, her composed façade is teared away by her aggrieved husband leading to a violent confrontation.</p> <h2>Only God Forgives</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H--z1M-524E\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/H--z1M-524E?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>While Nicolas Winding Refn’s atmospheric Drive followup might have included even less Ryan Gosling dialogue than before, Scott Thomas was allowed a string of perverse one-liners to inflict on her on-screen son. The cruelest of which were in this nightmarish family dinner, which borders on camp, but is difficult to ignore, thanks to Scott Thomas’ platinum blonde theatrics.</p>","headline":"Kristin Scott Thomas: five best moments","trailText":"The greatest English and French performances from the star of Suite Française","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/13/1426246028390/002a3a3c-6c88-4c8e-b227-acad7416b1b1-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"391","commentable":"true","byline":"Benjamin Lee","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-03-16T14:30:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/filmblog/2015/mar/13/kristin-scott-thomas-five-best-moments","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/filmblog/2015/mar/13/kristin-scott-thomas-five-best-moments","sectionName":"Culture","tags":