deo review\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426173446976/crop_640x360.jpeg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-455871183\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426173442282/crop_1200x720.jpeg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_desk.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_small.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://multimedia.guardianapis.com/interactivevideos/video.php?octopusid=10140174&amp;format=video/3gp&amp;minwidth=700\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_synd_768k_vp8.webm\"></source> </video> <figcaption>X+Y - video review</figcaption> </figure>  <p>His mother – an intelligent, compassionate performance from Sally Hawkins – must deal with it all as best she can. But then a troubled school maths teacher (Rafe Spall) enters Nathan for the maths Olympiad and there he finds his unemotional world rocked by an even more brilliant, beautiful maths whiz from China: Zhang Mei (Jo Yang). It’s an engaging film with a nice supporting performance from Eddie Marsan as the Olympians’ team coach, though the Olympiad itself turns out to be, somewhat oppressively, just one big, glorified exam, and the narrative question of whether some things are more important than maths is only really broached at the end of the film. But this is an attractively unparochial drama with a bracing interest in excellence.</p>","headline":"X+Y review – a charming mathematical uncertainty","trailText":"Competitive maths + teenage romance = an intelligent and engaging entertainment","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/11/14260967