6-ba4a-3b444fee4801-1024x768.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/9/19/1411156309611/02f447bb-db53-4826-ba4a-3b444fee4801-1024x768.jpeg","source":"Take Shelter","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Still from Take Shelter","height":"768","credit":"Photograph: Take Shelter","caption":"TAKE SHELTER, film still TAKE SHELTER, film still","mediaId":"gu-fc-12bafa03-3d22-400c-b268-49d1291a600a","picdarUrn":"GD*26024285","width":"1024"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"The November Man – first look review: an asinine and horribly rote screenplay","webPublicationDate":"2014-08-28T15:10:14Z","sectionId":"film","id":"film/2014/aug/28/the-november-man-pierce-brosnan-first-review","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4x4q9","standfirst":"<p>There’s no way around this: The November Man is impenetrable and not even Pierce Brosnan can save this absurdist action flick</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>There’s no way around this: The November Man is asinine. It is not without its pleasures – if you like seeing people get hit in the face with shovels, that is – but it might be the most irresponsibly dumb spy thriller I’ve seen in some time. It seems we can’t go a week without another mid-budget action film from a slew of international producers, a recognizable face out front practically bullying us to make a <a href=\"http://www.redbox.com/\">Redbox</a> rental. (Holding a gun and scowling usually reduces me to “yes, sir” obedience.) Unlike the Expendables or Getaway or any number of Nicolas Cage flicks, you can at least rationalize that this one is a slight cut above the others. If those are McDonald’s and Burger King, this one is at least The Olive Garden – it’s no less recycled, but the existence of a cloth napkin allows for the facade of decency.</p> <p>This film’s cloth napkin comes in the form of Pierce Brosnan. He who began his career as a fake James Bond on TV’s Remington Steele and then inherited 007’s license to kill during the franchise’s leaner years is, one cannot deny, a welcome and charismatic face up there on the big screen. Even when he’s galumphing through a screenplay that is simultaneously impenetrable and horribly rote. That’s a neat storytelling trick, so let me shed a little light on the actual plot of this idiotic movie. You may want to grab a shot of espresso for this next paragraph.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-7854f1c8-92f2-44ff-9706-f4c3e7e22d22\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/8/28/1409235741379/89fa9c0a-0c30-4026-84a7-5fba356ffbb9-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"november man pierce brosnan olga kurylenko\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Pierce Brosnan and Olga Kurylenko. Photograph: Aleksandar Letic/AP</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Peter Devereaux (Brosnan) gets results! He’s the best the CIA’s got, but after an op in Montenegro goes wrong, he leaves the agency to live in Switzerland. But now there’s a new threat – a real gross bad guy who is about to become the elected president of Russia! Someone on the inside has the goods to take this creep down and she needs to get extracted through Belgrade – and the only one who can do it is Devereaux.</p> <p>Well, guess what happens: things don’t go as planned. Do you think the people in high places that were originally trustworthy turn out, in fact, to be working toward a nefarious end? Or how about people who seem, at first, to be bad guys – might they, at the end of the day, do what’s right? I know you are sitting there, quaking in suspense to find out the answer.</p> <p>These hackneyed devices would be fine if the movie had anything to say or, at the very least, a jazzy way of not saying anything. The movie, alas, has neither. It has dull action set pieces, leaden dialogue, lots of running around Belgrade (making very little use of location photography) and endless Skype calls. There are some headfakes toward themes about how the act of killing leads to an irredeemable life, and there’s some father-son stuff between Brosnan and his former protégé played by Australian Luke Bracey, but these are fleeting whiffs. The movie only excels in its sound design department – an inordinate amount of people get bonked with pipes, fire extinguishers and full beer kegs in this one. Most likely because that’s cheap to film.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-f0a56d6f-5f11-4d2d-aa7e-78b2311f3ae1\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/8/28/1409234726442/20866bdb-b030-456c-afc7-6efd7e18cae4-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Olga Kurylenko november man\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The movie reduces Kurylenko’s character to a mere damsel that needs to be saved by a Hollywood-approved Anglo Saxon male. Photograph: Aleksandar Letic /AP</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In the middle of all this noise is a doe-eyed Chechen refugee played by Olga Kurylenko, and the movie finds plenty of opportunities to insultingly slap her down. First, the Second Chechen War is reduced to a silly plot point to scoot our backstory along. (Spoiler: turns out the root causes of this complex international tragedy is really just due to one man’s megalomaniacal movement of puppet strings.) Then, to make matters worse, when she finally has the fiend who killed her family and raped her all through her childhood in her clutches, Brosnan (and, by extension, the movie) reduces her once again to a mere damsel that needs to be saved by a Hollywood-approved Anglo Saxon male. Despicable. (More sexism abounds in this odious picture. Even though he’s a baddie, one character’s frequent reference to a female underling as either “tits” or “twat” is played for laughs. It isn’t funny.)</p> <p>Director <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0002044/\">Roger Donaldson</a> has made some terrific movies in the past (The Bounty, Thirteen Days) so I spent much of the film’s running time trying to give him the benefit of the doubt. A recurring motif is how young Luke Bracey can never catch Brosnan because he taught the kid everything he knows. This manifests itself in two scenes – one, a chase through a marketplace as the two trade barbs via cellphones, and the other where Brosnan nearly kills an innocent woman to test his former apprentice’s reflexes. I thought, for a moment, that this signaled a tipping point where the movie would show that the life of a killer had driven Brosnan past the point of redemption. But ... not really. Bracey’s young paramour, who gets three lines in the movie (but does get fully naked) has her femoral artery brutally sliced and is now scarred for the rest of the movie, all to show what a badass our hero is. The phrase “what the hell were they thinking?” comes to mind.</p> <p>The film does end “up,” with a bloody kill-spree that is, if nothing else, energetic. The audience packed with winners of a free ticket giveaway stopped talking amongst themselves for those scenes and seemed to have a good time.</p>","headline":"The November Man – first look review: an asinine and horribly rote screenplay","trailText":"There’s no way around this: The November Man is asinine and not even Pierce Brosnan can save this absurdist action flick","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/8/28/1409235651485/22f37864-fa1d-4786-ae76-6f8c3cecf400-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"922","commentable":"true","starRating":"2","byline":"Jordan Hoffman","productionOffice":"US","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-08-31T11:15:00-04:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/28/the-november-man-pierce-brosnan-first-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2014/aug/28/the-november-man-pierce-brosnan-first-review","sectionName"